Affirmative side.content:
{
  "debate_topic": "In a country, all families want a boy. They keep having babies till a boy is born. What is the expected ratio of boys and girls in the country?",
  "my_position": "The expected ratio of boys to girls in the country is 1:1",
  "key_arguments": [
    {
      "argument": "Each birth is an independent event",
      "explanation": "The probability of having a boy or girl is 0.5 for each birth, regardless of previous births or family preferences. This fundamental probability doesn't change based on when families decide to stop having children."
    },
    {
      "argument": "Expected value calculation",
      "explanation": "Let's consider what happens across all families: Half of families will have a boy on their first try (contributing 1 boy, 0 girls). A quarter will have a girl then a boy (contributing 1 boy, 1 girl). An eighth will have two girls then a boy (contributing 1 boy, 2 girls), and so on. The expected number of girls per family equals the expected number of births minus 1, which is 1. Every family contributes exactly 1 boy, so the ratio is 1:1."
    },
    {
      "argument": "Mathematical proof",
      "explanation": "Expected boys per family = 1 (by definition, every family stops at exactly one boy). Expected girls per family = Σ(n=0 to ∞) n × (1/2)^(n+1) = 1. Therefore, across the entire population, the expected ratio is 1 boy : 1 girl = 1:1."
    }
  ],
  "conclusion": "Despite the stopping rule that families only stop when they have a boy, the expected ratio of boys to girls remains 1:1. The stopping rule affects family size distribution but not the overall gender ratio in the population."
}

